<section class="card">
  <h2>What Jewel Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Jewel is best for gardeners who want a dependable main-crop June-bearing strawberry for fresh eating and preserving.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is not a day-neutral type, so expect a seasonal flush rather than steady all-summer production.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Jewel Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Strawberries are different from annual vegetables because the planting is meant to produce over multiple seasons.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season fit depends on winter survival, bloom timing, variety type, and whether you want one main crop or repeated harvests.
  </p>

  <p>
    Day-neutral varieties can fruit over a longer window, while June-bearing varieties concentrate harvest into a shorter season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Jewel</h2>

  <p>
    Plant strawberries in spring when the soil can be worked and plants can establish before heat or drought stress. Fall planting can work in some climates where plants have time to root before winter.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use healthy crowns or transplants, and do not bury the crown too deep. The crown should sit at the soil surface with roots covered.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/strawberries/">strawberry growing guide</a> and your frost dates. Winter protection and spring bloom timing matter as much as planting date.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Jewel</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Plant at the right depth:</strong> Buried crowns can rot, while exposed roots dry out.</li>
    <li><strong>Use a clean bed:</strong> Strawberries compete poorly with weeds.</li>
    <li><strong>Mulch plants:</strong> Mulch conserves moisture, keeps fruit cleaner, and can help with winter protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Water steadily:</strong> Moisture stress reduces establishment and fruit size.</li>
    <li><strong>Manage runners:</strong> Runner management depends on whether you want matted rows or spaced plants.</li>
    <li><strong>Protect fruit:</strong> Netting or row cover may be needed where birds or frost are problems.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Use</h2>

  <p>
    Harvest strawberries when berries are fully colored and sweet. They do not improve much after picking, so timing matters.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pick regularly during the harvest window. Overripe fruit attracts pests and disease.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use berries fresh, frozen, jammed, or baked. Day-neutral types may give smaller repeated harvests, while June-bearing types often give a more concentrated crop.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Jewel</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting crowns too deep:</strong> A buried crown can rot or grow poorly.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting weeds take over:</strong> Weeds reduce plant vigor and make picking harder.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting a full crop immediately:</strong> New strawberry beds often need establishment time.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring winter protection:</strong> Cold injury can reduce spring harvests.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing the wrong harvest pattern:</strong> Day-neutral and June-bearing strawberries behave differently.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Jewel vs Other Strawberry Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with other strawberry varieties, Jewel should be chosen for harvest pattern, flavor, winter hardiness, and disease pressure. Day-neutral and June-bearing types are not interchangeable in the garden plan.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this crop, the better choice depends on what you want from the harvest. Jewel is worth growing when its maturity window, plant habit, and kitchen use match your garden better than a faster, larger, or more specialized alternative.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Jewel?</h2>

  <p>
    Jewel is a good choice if its harvest pattern matches how you want to pick and use strawberries.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is less useful when the bed is poorly prepared or when winter protection, watering, and weed control are ignored.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>

  <p>
    Jewel can be a good choice when the timing matches your spring conditions, winter pattern, and growing season length. The exact planting window still depends on where you garden.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before choosing a planting date, check your local frost window and crop timing. A variety can fit short seasons well and still underperform if it is planted too late, started too late indoors, or grown in poor conditions.
  </p>

